      Celsius
   =20
 =20

A week ago, in an item about Celsius Network,=C2=A0I wrote that =E2=80=9Cev=
eryone who has paid attention to crypto over the past few years has their o=
wn personal top-10 list of =E2=80=98why aren=E2=80=99t those people in jail=
?=E2=80=99=C2=A0projects.=E2=80=9D I=C2=A0guess I can cross a name off my l=
ist:

The former chief executive officer of bankrupt crypto lender Celsius Networ=
k Ltd. was charged with fraud and sued by three regulatory agencies over th=
e company=E2=80=99s collapse.
Alex Mashinsky, 57, was also charged with attempting to manipulate crypto c=
urrencies in federal court in New York Thursday. The Securities and Exchang=
e Commission, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission and the Federal Trad=
e Commission also filed lawsuits against Mashinsky and the company.

Yes! Well.=C2=A0Yes. Here are (1) the Justice Department=E2=80=99s=C2=A0pre=
ss release,=C2=A0Celsius=E2=80=99s  non-prosecution agreement and  Mashinsk=
y=E2=80=99s indictment, (2) the SEC  press release and  complaint, (3) the =
CFTC  press release and  complaint and (4) the FTC  press release and  comp=
laint.=C2=A0
We have   talked a   lot about   Celsius around   here, because it was perh=
aps the most ridiculous of the big crypto companies. Celsius was a crypto l=
ending platform that offered customers high yields on their crypto deposits=
. In   an interview with Bloomberg Businessweek, Mashinsky explained that C=
elsius=E2=80=99s rates were so much higher than bank deposit rates not beca=
use it was riskier than a bank, but because it passed along more of its ear=
nings to customers. =E2=80=9CSomebody is lying,=E2=80=9D said Mashinsky: =
=E2=80=9CEither the bank is lying or Celsius is lying.=E2=80=9D
Last summer Celsius   froze customer withdrawals and   filed for bankruptcy=
. There are four long federal complaints against Celsius today, detailing i=
ts operations and the problems with them, and I will discuss them below. Bu=
t all of this is just a footnote to that sales pitch. =E2=80=9CEither the b=
ank is lying or Celsius is lying=E2=80=9D is everything you need to know ab=
out Celsius; a generative AI model could write all four of these complaints=
 with no prompt but that sentence;=C2=A0everything that Celsius actually di=
d is somehow contained in that sentence.=C2=A0
Celsius was allegedly engaged in two related investment scams: There was it=
s=C2=A0business, which involved getting customers to deposit cryptocurrenci=
es with Celsius, promising them safe=C2=A0yields of as much as 17%=C2=A0on =
their money, and then lending it out to crypto hedge funds; and there was i=
ts=C2=A0token, which was a form of quasi-stock=C2=A0in Celsius, a way for i=
nvestors to bet on Celsius=E2=80=99s success. The business was allegedly a =
scam because Celsius couldn=E2=80=99t generate safe 17% yields (obviously!)=
, and the token was allegedly a scam in the normal way that penny-stock pro=
motions are scams: Celsius allegedly lied about how good its business was t=
o get people to buy its token. Here=E2=80=99s the SEC=E2=80=99s summary:

Celsius marketed two core investment opportunities to investors. First, Cel=
sius offered and sold its own crypto asset security, CEL. Defendants promis=
ed high earning rates to investors who purchased CEL and marketed CEL as an=
 investment in the success of Celsius itself. Second, Celsius offered an Ea=
rn Interest Program whereby investors tendered their crypto sets to Celsius=
 in exchange for interest payments. Defendants promised investors in the Ea=
rn Interest Program returns as high as 17%. =E2=80=A6
Defendants made numerous false and misleading statements to induce investor=
s to purchase CEL and invest in the Earn Interest Program. Among other fals=
e representations, Defendants misrepresented Celsius=E2=80=99s central busi=
ness model and the risks to investors by claiming that Celsius did not make=
 uncollateralized loans, the company did not engage in risky trading, and t=
he interest paid to investors represented 80% of the company=E2=80=99s reve=
nue.
None of these claims was true. Celsius could not consistently generate the =
revenue needed to make the required interest payments to investors with res=
pect to the Earn Interest Program. The company engaged in risky trading pra=
ctices and made uncollateralized loans to try to generate the necessary rev=
enue, putting the entire Celsius enterprise at grave risk. Celsius was unsu=
ccessful and, as a result, frequently paid much more than 80% of its revenu=
e to satisfy the company=E2=80=99s interest payment obligations, a business=
 practice that was hidden from investors, unsustainable, and ultimately led=
 to the company=E2=80=99s collapse.

These things are intertwined: Lying to the customers to get them to deposit=
 money made the company=C2=A0look better to CEL investors, and pumping up t=
he price of CEL made Celsius=E2=80=99s balance sheet better and thus attrac=
ted more customers. (Also, Celsius paid some of the interest that it owed t=
o customers=C2=A0in CEL tokens, so the more they were worth the easier it w=
as to pay the customers.)
Let=E2=80=99s start with the business. Celsius advertised to customers that=
 they could deposit crypto, Celsius would pool their crypto and make good l=
ow-risk collateralized loans to institutional crypto investors, it would ge=
t paid interest on those loans, it would pass along 80% of that interest to=
 its customers, and somehow=C2=A080% of the interest it received on low-ris=
k collateralized loans would work out to be 17%? Somehow Celsius was making=
 loans that were both safe and lucrative. Either the bank is lying or Celsi=
us is lying. Which could it be? The SEC says:

A central tenet of Celsius=E2=80=99s promotion of its business was that it =
did not make uncollateralized loans when deploying investor funds from the =
Earn Interest Program. Celsius and Mashinsky made this representation frequ=
ently and in numerous different outlets. For example, in a November 26, 201=
9 livestreamed event, Mashinsky said: =E2=80=9CI can tell you there are oth=
er lenders in the market who lend with no collateral or lend to anybody. Go=
od. Good for them. We will never do that.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
In reality, despite the numerous public assurances to the contrary, Celsius=
 made many uncollateralized institutional loans totaling millions of dollar=
s. In fact, in November 2019, Celsius had more than $17 million in uncollat=
eralized institutional loans. ...
By 2022, Celsius=E2=80=99s uncollateralized institutional loans ranged from=
 $1.3 billion to $1.96 billion in value and accounted for 34-48% of the com=
pany=E2=80=99s entire institutional loan portfolio.

Celsius had enough of a compliance function that (1) they knew Mashinsky wa=
