  [2] When I was an equity derivatives banker, I made dumb jokes about =E2=
=80=9Cequity-financed share repurchases.=E2=80=9D This is basically that, t=
hough technically it=E2=80=99s tokens, not equity.


  [3] It rhymes. You=E2=80=99re using new investor money (from the OTC desk=
) to pay out old investors (in public-market buys).


  [4] Incidentally it is also a *little* reminiscent of my favorite part of=
 the Piggly-Wiggly corner that is famously described in John Brooks=E2=80=
=99s =E2=80=9CBusiness Adventures=E2=80=9D: Clarence Saunders cornered the =
stock but then faced the problem of how to realize his profits, that is, ho=
w to sell the stock without crashing the price. He had the genius idea of s=
elling his shares =E2=80=9Con the installment plan=E2=80=9D: Buyers would h=
ave to put up a down payment and then pay the rest in quarterly installment=
s, and =E2=80=9Che would not turn over the stock certificates to the buyers=
 until the final installment had been paid.=E2=80=9D (This didn=E2=80=99t w=
ork, but I still think about it a lot, because it was a great idea.) If you=
 buy stock now and sell it forward, then you can contract the currently tra=
ding supply.


  [5] The Justice Department case against Mashinsky takes a kitchen-sink ap=
proach, alleging securities fraud (the criminal version of the SEC case), c=
ommodities fraud (the criminal version of the CFTC case) and wire fraud (th=
e Justice Department=E2=80=99s own thing).


  [6] I say that, but it is sort of obviously in the SEC=E2=80=99s interest=
 to bring cases like this *in order to* try to get good jurisdictional ruli=
ngs. If the SEC sues a crypto issuer for securities fraud, the crypto issue=
r will inevitably argue =E2=80=9Cno, these are not securities,=E2=80=9D and=
 a judge will have to decide if they=E2=80=99re securities or not, and that=
 decision will have some precedential weight. And if the issuer is *Alex Ma=
shinsky*, and he gets up and says =E2=80=9CYour Honor, either the SEC is ly=
ing or I=E2=80=99m lying,=E2=80=9D the judge is not going to have a lot of =
sympathy for him, and is more likely to rule that CEL and Celsius=E2=80=99s=
 earning program are both securities, and that will help the SEC in future =
cases. This is complicated by the fact that every other regulator is here t=
oo: A judge is also going to rule that these are commodities!


  [7] A plausible answer: Random weirdos who come up to the sportsbook want=
ing to make a big bet and claiming to have inside information probably don'=
t. But he did!


