ther the bank is lying or Celsius is lying=E2=80=9D is everything you need =
to know about Celsius; a generative AI model could write all four of these =
complaints with no prompt but that sentence;=C2=A0everything that Celsius a=
ctually did is somehow contained in that sentence.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius was allegedly engaged in two related i=
nvestment scams: There was its=C2=A0<em>business</em>, which involved getti=
ng customers to deposit cryptocurrencies with Celsius, promising them safe=
=C2=A0yields of as much as 17%=C2=A0on their money, and then lending it out=
 to crypto hedge funds; and there was its=C2=A0<em>token</em>, which was a =
form of quasi-<em>stock=C2=A0</em>in Celsius, a way for investors to bet on=
 Celsius=E2=80=99s success. The business was allegedly a scam because Celsi=
us couldn=E2=80=99t generate safe 17% yields (<em>obviously!</em>), and the=
 token was allegedly a scam in the normal way that penny-stock promotions a=
re scams: Celsius allegedly lied about how good its business was to get peo=
ple to buy its token. Here=E2=80=99s the SEC=E2=80=99s summary:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius marketed two core investment opportuni=
ties to investors. First, Celsius offered and sold its own crypto asset sec=
urity, CEL. Defendants promised high earning rates to investors who purchas=
ed CEL and marketed CEL as an investment in the success of Celsius itself. =
Second, Celsius offered an Earn Interest Program whereby investors tendered=
 their crypto sets to Celsius in exchange for interest payments. Defendants=
 promised investors in the Earn Interest Program returns as high as 17%. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Defendants made numerous false and misleading =
statements to induce investors to purchase CEL and invest in the Earn Inter=
est Program. Among other false representations, Defendants misrepresented C=
elsius=E2=80=99s central business model and the risks to investors by claim=
ing that Celsius did not make uncollateralized loans, the company did not e=
ngage in risky trading, and the interest paid to investors represented 80% =
of the company=E2=80=99s revenue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of these claims was true. Celsius could n=
ot consistently generate the revenue needed to make the required interest p=
ayments to investors with respect to the Earn Interest Program. The company=
 engaged in risky trading practices and made uncollateralized loans to try =
to generate the necessary revenue, putting the entire Celsius enterprise at=
 grave risk. Celsius was unsuccessful and, as a result, frequently paid muc=
h more than 80% of its revenue to satisfy the company=E2=80=99s interest pa=
yment obligations, a business practice that was hidden from investors, unsu=
stainable, and ultimately led to the company=E2=80=99s collapse.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These things are intertwined: Lying to the cus=
tomers to get them to deposit money made the company=C2=A0look better to CE=
L investors, and pumping up the price of CEL made Celsius=E2=80=99s balance=
 sheet better and thus attracted more customers. (Also, Celsius paid some o=
f the interest that it owed to customers=C2=A0<em>in </em>CEL tokens, so th=
e more they were worth the easier it was to pay the customers.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s start with the business. Celsius=
 advertised to customers that they could deposit crypto, Celsius would pool=
 their crypto and make good low-risk collateralized loans to institutional =
crypto investors, it would get paid interest on those loans, it would pass =
along 80% of that interest to its customers, and somehow=C2=A0<em>80% of th=
e interest it received on low-risk collateralized loans would work out to b=
e 17%</em>? Somehow Celsius was making loans that were both safe and lucrat=
ive. Either the bank is lying or Celsius is lying. Which could it be? The S=
EC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A central tenet of Celsius=E2=80=99s promotion=
 of its business was that it did not make uncollateralized loans when deplo=
ying investor funds from the Earn Interest Program. Celsius and Mashinsky m=
ade this representation frequently and in numerous different outlets. For e=
xample, in a November 26, 2019 livestreamed event, Mashinsky said: =E2=80=
=9CI can tell you there are other lenders in the market who lend with no co=
llateral or lend to anybody. Good. Good for them. We will never do that.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In reality, despite the numerous public assura=
nces to the contrary, Celsius made many uncollateralized institutional loan=
s totaling millions of dollars. In fact, in November 2019, Celsius had more=
 than $17 million in uncollateralized institutional loans. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By 2022, Celsius=E2=80=99s uncollateralized in=
stitutional loans ranged from $1.3 billion to $1.96 billion in value and ac=
counted for 34-48% of the company=E2=80=99s entire institutional loan portf=
olio.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius had enough of a compliance function th=
at (1) they knew Mashinsky was lying and (2) they tried to stop him, but th=
ey couldn=E2=80=99t:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In an exchange on the messaging ap=
plication Slack, a Celsius executive told a senior employee at the company:=
 =E2=80=9CI just told [Mashinsky] that the number [of unsecured loans] is i=
ncreasing and the overall ratio of collateral with institutions is going do=
wn. =E2=80=A6 I will talk to him. I said this numerous times.=E2=80=9D The =
executive=E2=80=99s message was prompted by a false statement Mashinsky had=
 made about the company=E2=80=99s loan portfolio in a November 6, 2020 AMA.=
</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky was doing =E2=80=9Cweekly livestream=
ed events called =E2=80=98Ask Mashinsky Anything=E2=80=99 (=E2=80=98AMAs=E2=
=80=99),=E2=80=9D in which he would lie about Celsius=E2=80=99s collateral,=
 and then Celsius would go back and edit out the lies later:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At a May 14, 2021 AMA, Mashinsky [said]: =E2=
=80=9CThese loans are collateralized. This means the institutions=C2=A0give=
 Celsius assets or dollars to hold onto before we give out the digital asse=
ts. This protects the community and keeps them whole.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky=E2=80=99s May 14 statement was delet=
ed as part of the AMA Editing Process, at the direction of a Celsius execut=
ive. That executive recognized the falsity of Mashinsky=E2=80=99s public st=
atement and noted: =E2=80=9CIt is crucial to: delete this section of the AM=
A, AND remove the curated video explanation from EVERYPLACE on the internet=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Celsius was allegedly lying about how safe =
its loans were. This turned out to be important! When Celsius ultimately fi=
led for bankruptcy, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/32072646.260409/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNlcy5zdHJldHRvLmNvbS9wdWJsaWMveDE5MS8xMTc0O=
S9QTEVBRElOR1MvMTE3NDkwNzE0MjI4MDAwMDAwMDA5Ni5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B45ef6bb7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> it reported</a> assets of $4.3 billion (including gross=
 loans of $930 million with a $310 million allowance for doubtful accounts)=
=C2=A0and customer liabilities of $4.7 billion (and total liabilities of $5=
.5 billion); it turned out that the loans were not nearly as safe as Celsiu=
s advertised, and so there is not enough money for the customers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Celsius was=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>allege=
dly lying about how=C2=A0<em>profitable=C2=A0</em>its loans were: Even thou=
gh it was making risky uncollateralized loans, it still couldn=E2=80=99t re=
ally generate enough revenue to pay out the returns it promised to customer=
s<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tran=
sparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky and other executives at Celsius fear=
ed losing investors as a result of the company lowering the interest rates =
it paid participants in the Earn Interest Program. As a result, Celsius lar=
gely set its interest rates in order to attract and retain investors rather=
 than the basing them on the returns it was able to receive from its busine=
ss activities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Contrary to Defendants=E2=80=99 many represent=
ations that 80% of revenue is paid to investors, Celsius consistently paid =
out more in interest than the company generated in revenue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This fact was well-known to Celsius executives=
, including Mashinsky. For example, in February 2021, Celsius=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0CFO sent Mashinsky a financial document showing that for 2020, Celsius p=
aid out $45.7 million in interest (called =E2=80=9Crewards=E2=80=9D) but ge=
nerated only $42.7 million in income. In other words, more than 100% of Cel=
sius=E2=80=99s revenue in 2020 went to pay purported interest to investors.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2021, Celsius paid 23% more in interest to =
investors in the Earn Interest Program than it generated in revenue.=C2=A0<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Celsius was losing money, while telling inv=
estors in its quasi-stock CEL token that it was making money, which is bad.=
 But also: If you raise money from customers by promising them high returns=
, and then you don=E2=80=99t earn enough revenue=C2=A0to pay those returns,=
 and you pay them anyway =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, where did you get the money t=
o pay them? If the answer is =E2=80=9Cventure capitalists bought stock in y=
our company and you used their investment to pay the returns,=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9Cyour wealthy CEO put some of his own money back into the company t=
o make customers whole,=E2=80=9D that might or might not be misleading depe=
nding on your disclosure, but those are basically good answers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s Celsius=E2=80=99s answer, which=
 of course it put explicitly in writing:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky and Celsius=E2=80=99s se=
nior leadership were aware that the company=E2=80=99s=C2=A0payout ratio was=
 above 100%, with one executive noting Celsius was =E2=80=9Cbasically using=
 user balances to pay user rewards.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s the bad answer! There=E2=80=99s=
 a name for that! If you raise money=C2=A0from customers promising them 17%=
 returns, and then you don=E2=80=99t make enough money to pay those returns=
, and then you raise more money=C2=A0from new customers and use some of the=
ir money to pay the returns, that=E2=80=99s a Ponzi scheme. Maybe you don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>mean=C2=A0</em>to do a Ponzi scheme, but if you go arou=
nd saying =E2=80=9Cwe use user balances to pay user rewards=E2=80=9D surely=
 you have some idea what you are doing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Celsius told its customers that it was maki=
ng safe investments to earn them high yields, but it was allegedly really m=
aking risky investments and also doing a bit of a Ponzi to get those yields=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there were the CEL tokens.=C2=A0The S=
EC says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since the founding of Celsius, CEL played a cr=
itical role in the company. In a March 2018 white paper, Celsius described =
CEL as the backbone of the Celsius Network. CEL was a token that unlocked d=
iscounts and features on Celsius=E2=80=99s platform, such that the greater =
the number of people who wanted to use the platform, the higher the demand =
would be for CEL.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On March 8, 2018, Mashinsky further explained =
in a livestreamed event: =E2=80=9CWe are focused on enabling the community,=
 on creating a large community because everything we do is measured by the =
[CEL] token.=E2=80=9D Mashinsky went on to say:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe token pri=
ce goes up, our entire compensation is the token. So our job is to do every=
thing we can to increase the price of the token as long as it=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0in the best interest of the community.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky also publicly described the price of=
 CEL as a measure =E2=80=9Cof the profitability or how well is Celsius doin=
g.=E2=80=9D In other words, the price of CEL would increase when Celsius su=
ccessfully attracted more users, and the price of CEL would decrease when t=
he demand for Celsius=E2=80=99s investment services declined.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Consistent with their public statements, Mashi=
nsky and others at Celsius viewed CEL as comparable to stock in a public co=
mpany. Mashinsky wrote in an internal message that he wanted =E2=80=9Cto be=
 able to talk about CEL just like public companies talk about their stock.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/32072646.260409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDcvd2hlbi1pcy1hLXRva2VuLW5vdC1hLXNlY3VyaXR5P2NtcG=
lkPUJCRDA3MTMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzb=
GV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDcxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB6bc3351c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  I agree with Mashinsky</a>: There is some a=
rguable=C2=A0<em>utility=C2=A0</em>to the CEL tokens; they could be used to=
 do stuff on the Celsius lending platform, but realistically they were just=
 stock in Celsius. The tokens went up when Celsius=E2=80=99s business was g=
ood, when people were more confident in Celsius and believed in its future;=
 the tokens were a bet on Celsius=E2=80=99s business. They were stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so, like any company with a publicly trade=
d stock, if Celsius were to, for example, lie about its business and financ=
ial condition, that would be securities fraud. So the SEC quotes Mashinsky =
saying in an April 2022 CNBC interview that Celsius had 1.7 million users, =
when in fact it had fewer than 500,000. Or in May 2022,=C2=A0Mashinsky twee=
ted =E2=80=9CCelsius has not experienced any significant losses and all fun=
ds are safe=E2=80=9D; meanwhile, says the SEC:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On May 9, 2022, just two days before Celsius a=
nd Mashinsky released their reassuring statements on Twitter, a Celsius exe=
cutive called the company a =E2=80=9Csinking ship.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On May 12 and 25, 2022, that same Celsius exec=
utive wrote in Slack exchanges that =E2=80=9Cthere is no hope =E2=80=A6 the=
re is no plan,=E2=80=9D and that Celsius=E2=80=99s business model is =E2=80=
=9Cfundamentally=C2=A0broken.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another employee bluntly stated in an internal=
 message on May 21, 2022: =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have any profitabl=
e services.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky knew Celsius=E2=80=99s continued via=
bility was in doubt. A Celsius executive told Mashinsky in a May 25, 2022 m=
essage: =E2=80=9C[W]e will continue to dig a deeper hole for many months an=
d the asset/liability gap is much more severe now with lower balances.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The standard stuff of a securities-fraud case.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, though, Celsius was allegedly manipulati=
ng the price of its CEL token by secretly buying it in the public market. T=
here is a bit of a strange dynamic here, because there were two ways to buy=
 and sell CEL tokens. =E2=80=9CAccredited investors in the United States co=
uld purchase and sell CEL directly from and to Celsius through the company=
=E2=80=99s over-the-counter desk (=E2=80=98OTC=E2=80=99),=E2=80=9D says the=
 SEC; if you bought from the OTC desk your tokens were locked up for one ye=
ar, for securities-law reasons. But CEL tokens were also listed on various =
crypto trading platforms. The trading platforms were public; the OTC desk w=
as not =E2=80=94=C2=A0and, because of the lockup, CEL tokens sold OTC could=
 not immediately be traded on the public markets. =E2=80=9CBecause these [O=
TC] transactions occurred on the Celsius platform, they were only reflected=
 in internal records and not on the blockchain or to other users of the Cel=
sius platform.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there is sort of a dumb trade<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
