important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Celsius can sell 1 million=C2=A0token=
s OTC for, say, $1 each.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It can us=
e the $1 million to buy back slightly fewer than 1 million tokens on the pu=
blic markets, driving the price up to, say, $1.05.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">
<em>This is bad</em>, for Celsius, as a matter of corporate finance:=C2=A0I=
t issues more tokens than it buys back; it sells low to buy high.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But =E2=80=94=C2=A0because Celsius=E2=80=99=
s purchases reduce the public supply and drive the price up, while its OTC =
sales do=C2=A0<em>not </em>immediately=C2=A0increase the public trading sup=
ply or drive the price down =E2=80=94=C2=A0it has the effect of manipulatin=
g the price of CEL up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because Cel=
sius=E2=80=99s treasury consists largely of CEL tokens (which Celsius just =
made up), driving up the price of CEL has the effect of making Celsius look=
 bigger and more creditworthy and giving it more financial flexibility: Dri=
ving up the price of an asset that you control makes you richer.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also, the <em>next</em> time you sell 1 mill=
ion tokens OTC, you can sell them at the new market price of $1.05.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or here is how Celsius described its manipulat=
ion plan in a memo, according to the SEC:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An internal memo stated as its =E2=80=9CMain T=
hesis=E2=80=9D to increase the price of CEL, =E2=80=9C[w]e rise and fall wi=
th CEL=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9C[t]he more customer[s] use CEL &amp; the =
more it=E2=80=99s worth, the more worth we can extract out of it (for examp=
le using it for interest payments instead of our [c]ash).=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The internal memo described a plan to raise th=
e price of CEL. The plan included =E2=80=9C[v]alue based repurchase example=
s=E2=80=9D in which Celsius would repurchase certain percentages of the CEL=
 it sold via OTC =E2=80=9Con a case to case basis dependent on our Cash Nee=
ds.=E2=80=9D The memo also detailed a plan that would give =E2=80=9Cvalue t=
o CEL=E2=80=9D through Celsius=E2=80=99s increased trading activity:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The more CEL we sell OTC</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The more CEL we can repurchase</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The more attractive CEL markets look like</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The more CEL buy orders we receive</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In the end: The more our Treasury is wort=
h</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The less # of CEL we need to sel=
l for the same $ value we want to raise with these OTC sales</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not quite a Ponzi scheme,<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but it is an alarming business plan.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
