<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth=
 of CEL in your Treasury, you can make a business out of that. You can use =
this valuable CEL to pay interest to your customers. You can sell some CEL =
over-the-counter, subject to year-long lockups, to raise cash. You can=C2=
=A0get customers to lend you real money by saying =E2=80=9Cour balance shee=
t is strong, look how valuable our assets are.=E2=80=9D If you have a lot o=
f assets, you can attract more assets. You might be tempted to manipulate t=
he value of your assets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally! I have been quoting above mostly=
 from the SEC complaint, though the Justice Department and CFTC and FTC cov=
er similar ground. This mostly reveals my own biases: I think of this as pr=
imarily an SEC case, because it feels to me like a=C2=A0very classic=C2=A0<=
em>securities fraud</em>. Celsius allegedly did two things:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It told people =E2=80=9Cgive us your =
money and we will invest it and earn 17% for you risk-free,=E2=80=9D and th=
en lost their money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It told peopl=
e =E2=80=9Cwe are a great business, buy our stock,=E2=80=9D but it was lyin=
g and also manipulating the price of the stock.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That first thing is just a classic investment =
scam; the second is a classic penny-stock pump-and-dump. It is all standard=
 fare for the SEC, and for the Justice Department (because the SEC can=E2=
=80=99t bring criminal charges).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
